NITRATE CONCENTRATIONS IN SURFACE WATER by Tim Franken

Introduction to the data

The dataset for this project is a datset related to water quality measurements in small rivers in Flanders. The dataset has 4211 rows of 15 variables:

  • nitrate: Yearly maximum nitrate concentration in the river [mg N/L]
  • year: Year of measurement
  • rainfall: Cumulative rainfall in the month leading up to the measurement
  • oxygen: Oxygen saturation
  • area: area of farmland divided by total upstream area. 0 –> no farming, 1 –> all farmland
  • emission: emmission of N by animals divided by area of farmland
  • stockage: stockage of manure in a year
  • grass: area of grass divided by area of farmland
  • vegetableG1: area of vegetables in group G1 divided by area of farmland
  • vegetableG2: area of vegetables in group G2 divided by area of farmland
  • vegetableG3: area of vegetables in group G3 divided by area of farmland
  • catchcrop: Factor indicating whether yes or no a catchcrop is planted. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catch_crop)
  • norm_N: threshold of N to be applied on the field
  • depostion: depostion of N from the air in the total upstream area.

What we are mainly interested here is to see if any of these variables can explain the variance in the nitrate concentrations in the river.

The main variable that we are interested in is nitrate concentrations in the river. By law there is a threhsold of 11.3 mg N/L.

## [1] 0.2524341

We also want to take a look at the other variables.

Oxygen has a lot of 0 measurements. These are measurements that are below the detection limit. This is important to remember once we start building our model. We still have 2620 measuremnts or about 62% of the total if we would eliminate those with 0 measurements.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The initial dataset consists of 4211 rows and 15 variabales. Each row consists of a nitrate measurement at a certain location along with some other variables linked to it.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main variable of interest is the nitrate concentrations in the surface water. This concentration is still too high (related to the allowed threshold) in a number of locations despite lot of efforts.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The bivariate analysis might reveal some variables that correlate to the overall measured nitrate concentrations. However, since a lot of processes determine the final concentrations we don’t expect very strong relations.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created the total_Veg variable which is the sum of the different groups of vegetables in the original dataset.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I removed some outliers in the depostion variable. Apart from that we need to note that there are a lot of 0 measurements in the oxygen variable that might influence further analysis.

Let’s investigate the correlations between some other quantitative variables.

Based on this information, let’s take a closer look at some of the correlations.

Oxygen seems to have a rather high correlation coefficient.

As well as area.

From these plots it is clear that there is a correlation between both. Higher nitrate concentrations have in general higher areas. As a reminder, area indicates the proporation of farmland in the upstream area.

Yet it is also clear that a lot of other factors are influencing the concentrations.

Area is also strongly linked to deposition which in itself has an inverse relation to nitrate concentrations. This is rather unexpected as we would expect that farm activities have an influence on the depostion.

Also the variables emission, grass & total_veg have a small but existing correlation

Based on the plot we would assume that the correlation between total_veg & nitrate is higher that what we observed in the correlation scatter plot. This is due to the 0 values in the total_veg variable as can be seen by comparing the correlation coefficient in both.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot forms the basis for this exploration. It shows a histogram of nitrate concentrations in Flemish rivers, indicating the allowed threshold of 11.3 mg N/L. This plot clearly shows that there is a significant number of measurement locations that exceed this threshold.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot indicates that there is a relation between the proportion of farmland in the upstream area and the nitratte concentrations measured in the river. This is an important conclusion as it indicates that human behaviour is (partly) responsible for the measured concentrations. Yet it also becomes clear from this plot that there are still other influencing factors.

Plot Three

Description Three

This plot shows the comparison between measured and predicted nitrate concentrations. The predicted concentrations are based upon a linear model that includes all relevant ariables that were included in the analysis. This plot shows that we can explain some of the observed variance based on these variables but definetly not all.

Reflection

This dataset contains 4211 measurments of nitrate and related variables in rivers in Flanders. About 25% of the measurement locations exceeds the prescribed threshold of 11.3 mg N/L. Based on a (rudimentary) trend analysis we can conclude that this number is decreasing over the past years.

We can conclude from the bivariate analysis that nitrate concentrations correlate well with oxygen in the water and the proportion of farmland in the upstream are. Also other variables such as the area of grassland, vegetable and emmission of N by animals is correlated with nitrate concentrations.

Furthermore we found that a large proportion of the data contains a high number of 0 values in the dataset. This is important to take into account in further investigations.

The linear model we set up indicated that we can explain some of the observed variance based on the variables in our dataset but definetly not all.

The dataset we used still contains a limited number of variables and does e.g. not contain any information related to physical or chemical properties of the soil such as e.g. soil texture which might influence nitrate concentrations as well. It might be worth repeating this analysis with those variables included.
